Since enjoying this awesome practice in September, the second lockdown here in England has had a negative effect on this senior yogi, so I had to do a little adjusting to see me through,  but I so loved the ‘ little bit of everything ‘ of this sequence, it was a fun party, slow and kind. @Gill Smith I so appreciate your advice! Today I was feeling very 😞, and I was going to use this plan of doing the morning yoga for beginners. It did get me on the mat! I saw that it was a 14 min practice today (Truth), read your comments to see if I needed to modify, and did the practice. I did a foot massage too. 💓 Gardening is such tough work. I am always amazed how people can do it and apply their knowledge of plants like that. It is such a gift 🌱

So important not to injure yourself Laura ! I have paid the price next day, by going a step too far in a challenging practice and learned to ease off when body tells me. Also after some what I call extreme gardening in the summer, I twinged my back digging out a large bush. But Adriene always comes to my rescue with a relevant practice to correct my injury. There’s always “Yoga for ..... “ if I search 😊 often if I’m feeling 😐 I just do Morning Yoga for Beginners or Gentle, Relaxing, Cozy Flow. This way I can never miss my daily yoga which so helps my mental state and keeps me positive. It’s been a shocking year ! See you on mat Laura 🧘🏼‍♀️😊🙏💕

@Gill Smith I love those ideas! I will join you in those child’s pose and neck circles. If I do too much like an extended vinyasa flow or side planks Are usually hurt myself and end up not being able to do yoga for maybe even a month while I’m healing. I so appreciate your response!

Yes Laura, I enjoy the more physical practices to keep me fit but sometimes things like side planks and fast vinyasa flows become a little too much, especially with my arthritis. So instead of feeling in despair, I accept my edge and miss out some vinyasas, go to child’s pose, relax, then meet back up in downward dog. I also do useful neck and shoulder circles and breathe deep when moves get tough, so relaxing, then join back in with the sequence. That keeps it fun😊 hope this helps 🧘🏼‍♀️😃💕

200-hour residential new to ashtanga yoga teacher training course in India with Yoga Alliance USA RYT 200 Certification at Yoga School Tattvaa Yogashala, Rishikesh

Tattvaa Yogashala offers the opportunity to journey into the depths of your yoga practice. Located in Rishikesh, the yoga capital of the world, on the banks of the holy Ganges River, our school offers a natural haven for those who seek an experience and environment in which to evolve in body, mind and spirit. We are globally known for world class Yoga Teacher Training in Rishikesh, India. Tattvaa Yogashala is a world renown yoga school specialising in the traditional Ashtanga system of yoga. For years our school has dedicated itself to sharing and spreading the knowledge of this miraculous lineage, continuing to inspire and evolve yoga practitioners around the world.

hi adriene! i'm not sure if you answer comments but i'm going to try: I have a really tense and inflexible lower back. i love yoga but i get very uncouraged because i can't i.e bend down with my back straight and stuff. do you have any tips for a very inflexible lower back?

@Heta
Happy to be able to help a bit. Glad you found some great videos. Keep enjoying the journey! xo
@Lucille Sanders thank you so much Lucille! this was very helpful and i already found some great videos to try out. thank you & take care love xx

Hi Heta. Either on You Tube or Adriene's website, in search, type lower back. Possibly alternate any lower back videos with other practices. Also, search hips, as Adriene teaches that often tightness in hips affects the back. And as Adriene would say, be gentle, do not force the stretch and breathe deeply into your lower back....feeling it expand even a tiny bit with the breath. I just did one of her videos where she is in the basic seated posture. She reminded us that if you watch some of her earliest videos from 8 years ago, when in seated position her hips were so tight her knees were no where near the floor. She herself has slowly become more flexible while teaching. I hope this helps a bit, as Adriene says they get so many comments they can't really respond to all. Be gentle with yourself. Be safe. Enjoy all that your body is doing for you. Take care. Lucille
